{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"46e36ab7-efb1-49f7-bb24-79288fa3e19d","content":"Here's a step-by-step diagnostic and fix plan:\n\n---\n\n## Phase 1 — Assess current state (read-only, safe)\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Which SDKs are installed?\ndotnet --list-sdks\n\n# 2. Which workloads are installed and what state are they in?\ndotnet workload list\n\n# 3. Check for workload update candidates (dry-run, changes nothing)\ndotnet workload update --dry-run\n\n# 4. Show the Android / MAUI manifest versions\ndotnet workload search maui\n```\n\nAlso check your `global.json` (repo root) — if it pins an older SDK band, the new SDK may be ignored or cause mismatches.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 2 — Diagnose the errors\n\n| Symptom | Likely cause |\n|---|---|\n| `NETSDK1147` / \"workload not installed\" | Workloads from old SDK band; new SDK doesn't see them |\n| `XA5300` / Android SDK component missing | Android SDK path mismatch or missing platform/build-tools |\n| `java.lang.UnsupportedClassVersionError` | JDK version too old for new Android build-tools |\n\n---\n\n## Phase 3 — Fix workloads\n\n`dotnet workload update` **is safe** — it updates manifests and packs to match your current SDK band. It doesn't touch your projects.\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Repair / update workloads (run elevated)\ndotnet workload update\n\n# 2. If that alone doesn't list maui, install it explicitly\ndotnet workload install maui\n\n# 3. Verify\ndotnet workload list\n#   → should show: maui, android, ios, maccatalyst, etc.\n```\n\n> **Rollback option:** `dotnet workload update --from-rollback-file` lets you pin exact manifest versions if `update` pulls something incompatible.\n\n---\n\n## Phase 4 — Fix Android SDK\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Confirm the SDK path .NET is using\ndotnet build -bl        # then inspect binlog, or check:\n#   Environment var:  ANDROID_HOME  or  ANDROID_SDK_ROOT\n#   Default path:     %LOCALAPPDATA%\\Android\\Sdk\n\n# 2. Open Android SDK Manager (or cmdline) and install what the\n#    new workload expects:\nsdkmanager --list\nsdkmanager \"platforms;android-35\" \"build-tools;35.0.0\"\n\n# 3. If you manage Android SDK via Visual Studio:\n#    Tools → Android → Android SDK Manager → install missing items\n```\n\nIf .NET can't find the SDK, set it explicitly in your `.csproj`:\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <AndroidSdkDirectory>C:\\path\\to\\Android\\Sdk</AndroidSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n---\n\n## Phase 5 — Validate\n\n```powershell\n# Clean rebuild\ndotnet clean\ndotnet build -c Debug -f net9.0-android   # adjust TFM to your version\n\n# Run on emulator / device\ndotnet build -t:Run -f net9.0-android\n```\n\n---\n\n**TL;DR:** `dotnet workload update` is non-destructive and is exactly the right first step. Follow it with an Android SDK component sync, then do a clean build. The dry-run flag (`--dry-run`) lets you preview changes before committing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1d1f28d9-e8bd-4a21-ad8a-aa060cf4e94b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory is empty. The user is asking for a diagnostic and fix plan, not for me to modify code. Let me provide a comprehensive plan based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI, workloads, and Android SDK management.","outputTokens":898,"requestId":"080C:348511:A9757D:C3CFF0:69F2A97C"},"id":"55007678-27f5-4661-91cd-9e265dfe6ae7","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:00:00.949Z","parentId":"0fb04765-2787-489a-b1f5-e78b8aedb8c0"}
